    "tagline": "The harbour the earthquake spared",
    "summary": "Fiskardo sits at Kefalonia's northern tip, the one village the 1953 earthquake left standing — so the waterfront still carries its Venetian-era pastel houses, ochre and rose and faded green, leaning over a horseshoe of clear water. The fishing fleet has dwindled to a handful of boats now, and yachts take their place along the quay, but the bones of the place are older and quieter than the polish suggests. Ithaca lies just across the channel, close enough to read its hills.\n\nBy day it is a slow procession along the promenade — bakeries, a few boutiques, tavernas that fill in the evening. We'd come more for the edges than the centre: the pine-shaded walk out to the twin lighthouses on the headland, the ruined Byzantine basilica, and the pebble coves nearby. It feels refined rather than rustic, and busiest at lunch when the day-trippers arrive. Early or late is when it breathes.",
