    "tagline": "The island's capital, where turtles surface",
    "summary": "Argostoli has been Kefalonia's capital since 1757, when life shifted down from the old hill town of Agios Georgios to the sheltered bay it still sits on. It is not a postcard village — it is the working heart of the island, rebuilt after the 1953 earthquake — and that ordinariness is part of the appeal. The Koutavos lagoon curls inland behind town, and the long stone De Bosset bridge, laid in 1813, walks you out over still water toward Drapano.\n\nWhat we come for is the morning. At the fish dock across from the cafés, loggerhead sea turtles drift in among the boats, chasing scraps from the catch — three or four at a time, close enough to watch without a boat or a ticket. After that it is coffee on the Lithostroto promenade, palm trees, a slow waterfront, and the lagoon's herons and ducks. Calm, lived-in, unhurried.",
