    "tagline": "The black-fir roof of the Ionian.",
    "summary": "Ainos is the highest peak in the Ionian — 1,628 metres of dolomite and limestone wearing a forest so dark the Venetians called it Monte Nero, the black mountain. That darkness is one tree: Abies cephalonica, the Kefalonian fir, endemic and dense from about 600 metres up. The road climbs out of the heat into cool, resin-scented air, and the whole island falls away beneath you — Zakynthos, the mainland mountains, the sea going pale at the edges.\n\nIt is a national park, quiet and unfussed, and it rewards slowness. We come for the air and the long views more than any single sight. Somewhere on the southeast flank a band of small semi-wild horses roams free; you may meet them, you may not, and the not-knowing is part of it. After the coast, an afternoon up here feels like stepping into a different, older Kefalonia.",
