    "tagline": "A quiet balcony over the Corinthian Gulf",
    "summary": "Aigio is where the trip begins gently — a working Achaean town stacked in three tiers above the Corinthian Gulf, chosen as a soft landing the night before the Patras ferry. It is not a resort and never pretends to be. Old stone raisin warehouses along the shore have become cafes that put their tables out by the train rails, the sea a few steps beyond, and the rhythm is unhurried even in August.\n\nFrom our sea-view room at Vrachos Suites, the water does the work. Climb to Psila Alonia, the green upper square with its 1900 tower, and the whole gulf opens out toward the mainland mountains. Down by the water, the Twelve Fountains feed one of Greece's oldest plane trees, and Panagia Tripiti sits on its cliff among cypresses. There is nothing here you must rush to see — which is exactly the point. Eat well, walk the front, sleep, and be at the port unhurried in the morning.",
