    "summary": "Lake Doxa sits at 900 metres in the Feneos valley, an artificial reservoir filled in the late 1990s and now so settled into its bowl of oak and fir that it reads as if it had always been here. The water is still and dark, the surrounding ridges fold in close, and on a clear morning the whole basin holds a quiet that feels almost held in place. People call this corner the Switzerland of Greece, which undersells the particular stillness of it.\n\nWhat you come for is the walk out along the thin spit to the little chapel of Agios Fanourios, marooned near the centre of the lake on its own peninsula. It is a short, flat path with water on both sides — unhurried, photogenic without trying. We fold this into the long drive east toward Athens on our last day: an hour and a quarter or so beyond Kalavryta, a place to stretch, breathe the pine, and let the trip wind down rather than rush its ending.",
