    "tagline": "Hot dry days, sea still warm",
    "summary": "Late August on the Ionian coast is the steady end of high summer — highs around 31°C, long dry days, and roughly twelve hours of sun. The sea has been warming all season and sits near 25-26°C, the warmest it gets all year, so a swim is reward rather than shock even late in the afternoon. Rain is rare. Humidity feels moderate near the water and the heat stays bearable in the shade.\n\nWhat sets the Ionian apart is the wind, or the lack of it. The meltemi that hammers the Aegean barely reaches us here — Kefalonia and Lefkada shelter the channels, and the prevailing breeze is the gentler northwest maistro. That means flat, glassy water on most mornings. Up in the Kalavryta mountains it is a different climate entirely: at around 820m, days still touch 30°C but evenings drop toward 17°C, so the air thins and cools the moment the sun goes down.",
