    "tagline": "Robola, thyme honey, and slow taverna nights",
    "summary": "Kefalonia eats from its own limestone. The island's signature is kreatopita — a meat pie of veal and lamb spiced with cinnamon and nutmeg, bound with rice and herbs under a tender crust — best found in village tavernas rather than the harbor fronts. Beside it pours Robola, the dry citrusy white grown on the slopes of Mount Ainos, in nearly every taverna by the carafe. Add thyme honey from the island's wildflower hills, aliada (the local garlic-and-potato skordalia) with salt cod or beets, a horiatiki salad heavy with feta, and whatever fish the day's catch happens to bring.\n\nWhat it feels like is unhurried. You order a few small plates, the carafe arrives sweating, and the table fills without a plan. On the Peloponnese leg the register shifts to mountain food around Kalavryta — grilled lamb and chops, hearty cheese-and-greens pies, and fresh trout pulled from the cold springs at Planitero. Two regions, one rhythm: long lunches, local wine, no rush to leave.",
